## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 5 Critical · 1 High · 1 Medium · 0 Low**

This test suite has systemic self-referential assertion problems. Six of eight tests assert that an output equals its input by choosing inputs that are already in the expected output state — making the assertions tautological. They inflate coverage while verifying almost nothing.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 72-77) — Always-True Assertion

The input `"HELLO"` is already uppercase. `"HELLO".ToUpper()` always returns `"HELLO"`, so `Assert.AreEqual(input, result)` can never fail. This test is dead weight.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — always passes, tests nothing
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// ✅ Fix — use an input that actually requires transformation
var input = "hello";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

---

#### 2. `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37-42) — Self-Referential Assertion

`Normalize()` does `Trim().ToLowerInvariant()`. The input `"alice"` is already trimmed and lowercase, so the output equals the input trivially. The test never verifies that normalization *actually transforms* anything.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — tautological; input is already normalized
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// ✅ Fix — test that transformation actually happens
[DataTestMethod]
[DataRow("  Alice  ", "alice")]
[DataRow("BOB", "bob")]
[DataRow("  CHARLIE ", "charlie")]
public void Normalize_TransformsInput(string input, string expected)
{
    var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

---

#### 3. `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 56-61) — Self-Referential Assertion

`GetDisplayName()` returns `Name` verbatim. Asserting `user.Name == display` is asserting `Name == Name` — a field against itself. The test name promises "formatted" output but asserts against the raw input.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — asserts a field against itself
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// ✅ Fix — assert against a literal expected value
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", display);
// If GetDisplayName should format (e.g., "Alice (30)"),
// assert that and fix the production code too.
```

---

#### 4. `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 46-53) — Tautological Round-Trip Hiding Data Loss

The mapping is **lossy**: `ToDto` drops `Id` and `Email` (sets `Age = 0`); `ToEntity` drops `Age` (sets `Id = 0`, `Email = ""`). A round-trip assertion on a lossy transform is fundamentally broken — it either silently asserts on destroyed data, or the assertions on `Id` and `Email` actually *fail* (`1 ≠ 0`, `"a@b.com" ≠ ""`), meaning this test may not even pass as written.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — round-trip on lossy mapping; Id and Email are destroyed
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Id, backToEntity.Id);       // 1 vs 0!
Assert.AreEqual(entity.FullName, backToEntity.FullName); // ok
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Email, backToEntity.Email);  // "a@b.com" vs ""!

// ✅ Fix — test each direction independently with expected values
[TestMethod]
public void ToDto_MapsFullNameToName()
{
    var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
    var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, dto.Age); // Age has no source — document this
}

[TestMethod]
public void ToEntity_MapsNameToFullName()
{
    var dto = new UserDto { Name = "Alice Smith", Age = 30 };
    var entity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", entity.FullName);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, entity.Id);    // Id is not mapped
    Assert.AreEqual("", entity.Email); // Email is not mapped
}
```

---

#### 5. `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 64-69) — Coverage Touching

This test only hits the happy path of `ValidateEmail` and asserts the return value equals the input — which is the trivial contract of "return what you got." The actual validation logic (the exception for invalid emails) is never exercised.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — only touches the pass-through path
var input = "hello@world.com";
var result = Validator.ValidateEmail(input);
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// ✅ Fix — keep the happy-path test but add validation coverage
[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_ValidInput_ReturnsInput()
{
    var result = Validator.ValidateEmail("hello@world.com");
    Assert.AreEqual("hello@world.com", result);
}

[TestMethod]
[DataRow("")]
[DataRow("   ")]
[DataRow("no-at-sign")]
public void ValidateEmail_InvalidInput_Throws(string input)
{
    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentException>(
        () => Validator.ValidateEmail(input));
}
